                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" hclass="sense" id="angryyoungman_sng_1"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="labels" hclass="labels" htag="span">(especially British English)</span></span> <span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">a young person who strongly criticizes political and social institutions. The phrase was originally used by British newspapers in the late 1950s, after the success of the play <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/look-back-in-anger" title="Look Back in Anger definition"><span class="ndv">Look Back in Anger</span></a> by <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/john-osborne" title="John Osborne definition"><span class="ndv">John Osborne</span></a>, to describe young British writers like Osborne, <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/kingsley-amis" title="Kingsley Amis definition"><span class="ndv">Kingsley Amis</span></a> and Alan Sillitoe.</span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
